+# DGX Spark GB10 Serving Benchmark Recipe
+
+This recipe shows a compact way to benchmark an already-running OpenAI-compatible
+vLLM server on an NVIDIA DGX Spark / GB10 workstation. It is intended as a
+starting point for local validation and regression checks, not as an official
+throughput claim for every model or configuration.
+
+## When to use this recipe
+
+Use this recipe when you want to compare two serving configurations on the same
+DGX Spark node, for example:
+
+- BF16 versus a quantized checkpoint
+- FP8 KV cache enabled versus disabled
+- different `--max-num-seqs` or `--max-num-batched-tokens` values
+- different OpenAI-compatible server startup flags
+
+Keep all other variables fixed when comparing results: model family, prompt
+set, sampling options, output length, vLLM commit, driver version, and hardware.
+
+## Start the server
+
+Start one vLLM server and leave headroom for the system. The exact model and
+serving flags depend on the checkpoint being tested.
+
+```bash
+vllm serve <model> \
+  --host 0.0.0.0 \
+  --port 8000 \
+  --gpu-memory-utilization 0.85 \
+  --max-num-seqs 4 \
+  --max-num-batched-tokens 32768
+```
+
+For quantized checkpoints, also record the quantization and KV-cache settings
+used to start the server. For example:
+
+```bash
+vllm serve <model> \
+  --host 0.0.0.0 \
+  --port 8000 \
+  --gpu-memory-utilization 0.85 \
+  --max-num-seqs 4 \
+  --max-num-batched-tokens 32768 \
+  --kv-cache-dtype fp8
+```
+
+Only run one large local server at a time on a single DGX Spark node unless you
+have separately validated multi-process memory pressure.
+
+## Run `vllm bench serve`
+
+Use the `random` dataset for a quick repeatable smoke benchmark:
+
+```bash
+vllm bench serve \
+  --backend vllm \
+  --model <model> \
+  --base-url http://127.0.0.1:8000 \
+  --endpoint /v1/completions \
+  --dataset-name random \
+  --random-input-len 128 \
+  --random-output-len 128 \
+  --num-prompts 27 \
+  --max-concurrency 1 \
+  --save-result \
+  --result-dir ./bench-results/dgx-spark-gb10
+```
+
+Increase `--max-concurrency`, input length, and output length after the smoke
+run is stable. For comparisons, keep the benchmark command identical across
+variants.
+
+## Report the result
+
+At minimum, include:
+
+- vLLM commit
+- model id and checkpoint format
+- GPU and driver version
+- server startup command
+- benchmark command
+- successful request count and error count
+- median and p95 TTFT
+- median ITL or TPOT
+- median output tokens/sec
+- memory headroom or OOM notes
+
+For example, a local single-node DGX Spark smoke run comparing the same workload
+across BF16 and a quantized checkpoint reported:
+
+| Variant | Requests | Success | Median TTFT | Median ITL | Median output tok/s |
+|---|---:|---:|---:|---:|---:|
+| BF16 | 27 | 100% | 0.128 s | 0.043 s | 22.76 |
+| Quantized | 27 | 100% | 0.126 s | 0.039 s | 25.10 |
+
+These numbers are workload-specific. Treat them as an example of the reporting
+shape, not as a guaranteed DGX Spark result.
+
+## Guardrails
+
+- Keep the machine responsive while benchmarking. Reserve CPU and memory
+  headroom for SSH, the kernel, and monitoring.
+- Do not compare runs that changed both the model and the serving flags.
+- Record failed requests and finish reasons; token/sec alone is not enough.
+- Run quality or behavior checks separately if the benchmark is used to support
+  a model-release claim.
